<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-05-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-05-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="578" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d578">
                        <head>No. 578.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">L. S.
                                    Sackville West</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-05-21"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 21, 1888</date>.
                                (Received May 22.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I am informed by the Marquis of Salisbury
                            that a number of Indians from Metlakahtla, in British Columbia, under
                            the leadership of a Mr. William Duncan, formerly a lay missionary of the
                            Church Missionary Society, have withdrawn from that point, and that from
                            information received have settled within the territory of Alaska.</p>
                        <p>It is presumed that such immigration and settlement is not contrary to
                            the immigration laws of the United States.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">L. S. Sackville
                                    West.</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>